+// Copyright (c) TriDB. Licensed under the MIT License.
+//
+// tjs_open_operator.cpp — TriDB `tjs_open` multi-seed open-domain retrieval operator
+// (ADR-0012 realization B / DEV-tjs-open).
+//
+// Marker for the patch sentinel grep (scripts/lib/msvbase_patches.sh): TRIDB: TJS-OPEN operator.
+//
+// WHAT THIS IS
+// ------------
+// `tjs_open` is the SEEDLESS sibling of the canonical single-source `tjs()` (ADR-0007). Where tjs()
+// is given ONE source vertex and returns the vector-nearest entities reachable from it, tjs_open
+// derives its OWN seeds from the vector leg, expands the graph from ALL of them, and ranks the
+// union — the validated host prototype (bench/tjs_open_ref.py, recall@10 ~0.987 on HotpotQA) made
+// an engine operator. It is ADR-0012 realization (B): the TR-1-pure, NON-blocking form. Realization
+// (A) (materialize ANN top-m UNION their neighbors, then rerank) is the BLOCKING reference oracle —
+// NOT shipped here.
+//
+//   tjs_open(table, k, term_cond, m_seeds, hops, attr, filter, order)
+//
+// THE PIPELINE (one streaming pass over the vector leg)
+// -----------------------------------------------------
+//   1. SEEDLESS SEEDING. Build ONE HNSW IndexScan over `order` with `filter` in its WHERE (exactly
+//      like tjs()'s vector leg). Pull the first `m_seeds` candidates off that ANN stream; their
+//      graph ids (attr's first column, by contract) are the personalization seeds. No caller `src`.
+//   2. MULTI-SOURCE GRAPH EXPANSION. BFS `hops` deep from the UNION of all seeds via
+//      graph_store.neighbors (the native adjacency-list iterator, golden rule 3 — never a relational
+//      join). The reachable union is the "bridge set": graph-relevant nodes that the pure vector
+//      ranking may rank far down or miss. Bounded by m_seeds * avg_deg^hops, NOT |V| — so caching it
+//      is a bounded buffer, not a full-corpus materialization (TR-1 holds; this is NOT realization A
+//      which materializes seed+reach AND reranks it as the whole answer).
+//   3. VECTOR-RANKED MERGE WITH BRIDGE INJECTION. Continue draining the SAME vector stream into a
+//      bounded top-k priority queue. A candidate is admitted to the heap when it improves the top-k
+//      (the ordinary vector winner) OR when it is in the bridge set (the injected bridge), EVEN if
+//      its vector rank is past the frontier. CRUCIAL for TR-1: a bridge admitted past the frontier
+//      does NOT reset the consecutive_drops counter — so the VBASE early-termination bound still
+//      fires. (This is the ADR-0012 (B) contract: "a graph-reachable candidate is admitted to the
+//      heap even when its vector rank is past the frontier, but it does NOT reset the drop counter".)
+//
+// FIRST-CUT vs THE HOST REFERENCE. This realizes the ADR-0012 *original* (B) recipe: vector-ranked
+// stream + reachability-set bridge injection + VBASE consecutive_drops termination. The 2026-06-29
+// addendum's refinement (bounded-push PPR graph *score* + NRA/FR termination + RRF rank-fusion) is
+// the STRETCH — modeled by bench/tjs_open_ref.py but NOT implemented in C here. The bridge set is a
+// reachability membership (in/out), exactly the original (B) "bridges" leg; PPR grading is a TODO.
+//
+// TR-1 (golden rule 1): Open/Next/Close + early termination. The only materialized set is the
+// bounded bridge set (a graph-local BFS, not the corpus); the vector stream is drained only until
+// consecutive_drops >= term_cond. Mirrors tjs() / multicol_topk exactly.
+//
+// The SPI / snapshot / SRF lifecycle is forked verbatim from tjs_operator.cpp (DEV-1236): one SPI
+// connection, one RegisterSnapshot pinned for the whole multi-call SRF, children torn down at the
+// finish label. The graph BFS reuses the SAME single SPI connection (graph_store.neighbors' own SPI
+// nests cleanly under ours) — never a sibling SPI_connect, the fork's signature crash.
+
